.TH "bathbuild" 1 "@BATH_DATE@" "BATH @BATH_VERSION@" "BATH Manual"

.SH NAME
bathbuild \- construct profiles from multiple sequence alignments


.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bathbuild
[\fIoptions\fR]
.I hmmfile_out
.I msafile


.SH DESCRIPTION

.PP
For each multiple sequence alignment in
.I msafile
build a profile HMM and save it to a new file
.IR hmmfile_out .
The profiles produced are suitable for use with
.BR bathsearch .

.PP
.I msafile
may be '\-' (dash), which means reading this input from stdin rather
than a file.

.PP
.I hmmfile_out
may not be '\-' (stdout), because sending the HMM file to stdout would
conflict with the other text output of the program.

.PP
If
.I msafile
contains a single unaligned sequence,
.B bathbuild
will construct a profile using a substitution score matrix rather than
the normal alignment-based approach. See the single sequence scoring
options below.


.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.B \-h
Help; print a brief reminder of command line usage and all available
options.

.TP
.BI \-n " <s>"
Name the new profile
.IR <s> .
The default is to use the name of the alignment (if one is present in
the
.IR msafile ),
or, failing that, the name of the
.IR hmmfile_out .
If
.I msafile
contains more than one alignment,
.B \-n
doesn't work, and every alignment must have a name annotated in the
.I msafile
(as in Stockholm #=GF ID annotation).

.TP
.BI \-o " <f>"
Direct the summary output to file
.IR <f> ,
rather than to stdout.

.TP
.BI \-O " <f>"
After each model is constructed, resave the annotated source alignment
to file
.I <f>
in Stockholm format. The alignment is annotated to show which columns
were assigned as consensus positions and the relative sequence weights
used in construction.

.TP
.BI \-\-ct " <n>"
Use the alternate genetic code specified by NCBI translation table
number
.IR <n> .
The default is 1 (the standard genetic code). This is used when the
model will be searched against DNA with
.BR bathsearch .


.SH OPTIONS FOR PROFILE CONSTRUCTION

These options control how consensus columns are defined in an alignment.

.TP
.B \-\-fast
Define consensus columns as those having a fraction >=
.I symfrac
of residues rather than gaps. This is the default. See
.BR \-\-symfrac .

.TP
.B \-\-hand
Define consensus columns using reference annotation in the multiple
alignment. This lets you specify exactly which columns are consensus.

.TP
.BI \-\-symfrac " <x>"
Set the residue fraction threshold used by
.B \-\-fast
to define consensus columns. The default is 0.5. Set to 0.0 to mark
every column as consensus; set to 1.0 to mark only gap-free columns.

.TP
.BI \-\-fragthresh " <x>"
Sequences whose aligned length is <=
.I <x>
times the total alignment length are treated as fragments, and their
terminal gaps are not counted as deletions. The default is 0.5.


.SH OPTIONS CONTROLLING RELATIVE WEIGHTS

.TP
.B \-\-wpb
Use the Henikoff position-based sequence weighting scheme. This is the
default.

.TP
.B \-\-wgsc
Use the Gerstein/Sonnhammer/Chothia tree-based weighting algorithm.

.TP
.B \-\-wblosum
Use single-linkage clustering at a fractional identity threshold (see
.BR \-\-wid )
to assign weights, as used in calculating BLOSUM matrices.

.TP
.B \-\-wnone
Assign uniform weight to all sequences; no relative weighting.

.TP
.B \-\-wgiven
Use weights as provided in the MSA file.

.TP
.BI \-\-wid " <x>"
Set the identity threshold for single-linkage clustering used by
.BR \-\-wblosum .
The default is 0.62.


.SH OPTIONS CONTROLLING EFFECTIVE SEQUENCE NUMBER

After relative weighting, sequence counts are normalized to an
effective sequence number.

.TP
.B \-\-eent
Adjust the effective sequence number to achieve a target relative
entropy per position. This is the default.

.TP
.B \-\-eclust
Set the effective sequence number to the count of single-linkage
clusters at the identity threshold given by
.BR \-\-eid .

.TP
.B \-\-enone
Use the actual number of sequences as the effective sequence number,
with no entropy-based adjustment.

.TP
.BI \-\-eset " <x>"
Explicitly set the effective sequence number for all models to
.IR <x> .

.TP
.BI \-\-ere " <x>"
Set the minimum relative entropy per position target to
.IR <x>
bits. Requires
.BR \-\-eent .
Default is 0.59 bits for protein and 0.45 bits for nucleotide.

.TP
.BI \-\-esigma " <x>"
Set the minimum total model relative entropy (summed over all positions)
to
.I <x>
bits. This raises the per-position entropy of short models.
The default is 45.0 bits.

.TP
.BI \-\-eid " <x>"
Set the fractional identity cutoff for single-linkage clustering used
by
.BR \-\-eclust .
The default is 0.62.


.SH OPTIONS CONTROLLING PRIORS

.TP
.B \-\-pnone
Do not use any prior. Probability parameters are the raw observed
frequencies after relative weighting.

.TP
.B \-\-plaplace
Use a Laplace +1 prior in place of the default mixture Dirichlet prior.


.SH OPTIONS CONTROLLING SINGLE SEQUENCE SCORING

When the query is a single sequence,
.B bathbuild
uses a substitution matrix to set residue probabilities. These options
control that behavior.

.TP
.B \-\-singlemx
If a single sequence query comes from an MSA-format file, force use of
the single-sequence substitution matrix method.

.TP
.BI \-\-mx " <s>"
Use the named built-in substitution matrix. The default is BLOSUM62.
Available choices include PAM30, PAM70, PAM120, PAM240, BLOSUM45,
BLOSUM50, BLOSUM62, BLOSUM80, BLOSUM90, and DNA1.

.TP
.BI \-\-mxfile " <f>"
Read a substitution matrix from file
.IR <f> ,
in standard BLAST/FASTA matrix format. Incompatible with
.BR \-\-mx .

.TP
.BI \-\-popen " <x>"
Set the gap open probability for single-sequence models to
.IR <x> .
Defaults are 0.02 (amino acid) and 0.031 (nucleotide).

.TP
.BI \-\-pextend " <x>"
Set the gap extend probability for single-sequence models to
.IR <x> .
Defaults are 0.4 (amino acid) and 0.75 (nucleotide).


.SH OPTIONS CONTROLLING E-VALUE CALIBRATION

Profile calibration fits score distributions using short random-sequence
simulations.

.TP
.BI \-\-EmL " <n>"
Sequence length for the MSV Gumbel mu calibration. Default is 200.

.TP
.BI \-\-EmN " <n>"
Number of sequences for the MSV Gumbel mu calibration. Default is 200.

.TP
.BI \-\-EvL " <n>"
Sequence length for the Viterbi Gumbel mu calibration. Default is 200.

.TP
.BI \-\-EvN " <n>"
Number of sequences for the Viterbi Gumbel mu calibration. Default is 200.

.TP
.BI \-\-EfL " <n>"
Sequence length for the Forward exponential tail tau calibration.
Default is 100.

.TP
.BI \-\-EfN " <n>"
Number of sequences for the Forward exponential tail tau calibration.
Default is 200.

.TP
.BI \-\-Eft " <x>"
Tail mass fraction for the Forward exponential tail tau calibration.
Default is 0.04.


.SH OTHER OPTIONS

.TP
.BI \-\-cpu " <n>"
Set the number of parallel worker threads to
.IR <n> .
On multicore machines, the default is 2. The environment variable
.B HMMER_NCPU
also controls this.
(Only available when BATH is compiled with thread support.)

.TP
.BI \-\-informat " <s>"
Assert that the input
.I msafile
is in alignment format
.IR <s> ,
bypassing format autodetection. Common choices include
.BR stockholm ,
.BR a2m ,
.BR afa ,
.BR psiblast ,
.BR clustal ,
.BR phylip .

.TP
.BI \-\-seed " <n>"
Set the random number seed to
.IR <n> .
The default is 42 (reproducible). A value of 0 uses a randomly chosen
seed.

.TP
.BI \-\-w_beta " <x>"
Set the tail mass used to determine the window length upper bound
.IR W .
The default is 1e-7.

.TP
.BI \-\-w_length " <n>"
Override the window length upper bound
.I W
directly. Should be larger than the model length.

.TP
.BI \-\-maxinsertlen " <n>"
Restrict insert length parameterization so that the expected insert
length at each model position is no more than
.IR <n> .


.SH SEE ALSO

.BR bathsearch (1),
.BR bathfetch (1),
.BR bathconvert (1),
.BR bathstat (1)

.PP
For complete documentation, see the BATH repository:
https://github.com/TravisWheelerLab/BATH


